sql:
SELECT products.product_name, warehouses.warehouse_name
FROM products
INNER JOIN warehouses ON products.warehouse_id = warehouses.warehouse_id;

SELECT DISTINCT c.customer_id, c.customer_name 
FROM customers c
INNER JOIN order_demand o ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

external_knowledge:
- 'items' refers to products in the inventory;
- 'product details' include product ID, product code, product name;
- 'what they contain' refers to the category name and description;
- 'who supplies them' refers to the supplier name and contact number;
- 'where they are stored' refers to the warehouse name and location;
- 'related order data' includes order ID, customer ID, order date, demand quantity, order status, and shipment date if applicable.

- "most popular items" refers to the products with the highest demand; 
- "best-selling items in terms of demand" means the products with the greatest number of units ordered; 
- "over the past month" means the period from now minus 30 days. 
- Each category's top items are determined based on the total demand for each product within the category.
